TY  - JOUR
T1  - On the Dynamics of Unemployment and Wage Distributions
AU  - Robin, Jean-Marc
Y1  - 2011/09/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/09/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA9070
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 1327
EP  - 1355
VL  - 79
IS  - 5
KW  - Unemployment dynamics
KW  - wage distribution
KW  - inequality
KW  - search-matching
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA9070
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Postel-Vinay and Robin's (2002) sequential auction model is extended to allow for aggregate productivity shocks. Workers exhibit permanent differences in ability while firms are identical. Negative aggregate productivity shocks induce job destruction by driving the surplus of matches with low ability workers to negative values. Endogenous job destruction coupled with worker heterogeneity thus provides a mechanism for amplifying productivity shocks that offers an original solution to the unemployment volatility puzzle (Shimer (2005)). Moreover, positive or negative shocks may lead employers and employees to renegotiate low wages up and high wages down when agents' individual surpluses become negative. The model delivers rich business cycle dynamics of wage distributions and explains why both low wages and high wages are more procyclical than wages in the middle of the distribution.
ER  - 

