TY  - JOUR
T1  - Apparent Overconfidence
AU  - Benoît, Jean-Pierre
AU  - Dubra, Juan
Y1  - 2011/09/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/09/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA8583
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 1591
EP  - 1625
VL  - 79
IS  - 5
KW  - Overconfidence
KW  - better than average
KW  - experimental economics
KW  - irrationality
KW  - signalling models
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA8583
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - It is common for a majority of people to rank themselves as better than average on simple tasks and worse than average on difficult tasks. The literature takes for granted that this apparent misconfidence is problematic. We argue, however, that this behavior is consistent with purely rational Bayesian updaters. In fact, better-than-average data alone cannot be used to show overconfidence; we indicate which type of data can be used. Our theory is consistent with empirical patterns found in the literature.
ER  - 

